{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/vim-the-ubiquitous-text-editor-b4e09374df57", "time": 1683005004.85072, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/vim-the-ubiquitous-text-editor-b4e09374df57/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "\u201cVim \u2014 the ubiquitous text editor\u201d | by Shivangi Sareen | Towards Data Science", "h1": "\u201cVim \u2014 the ubiquitous text editor\u201d", "description": "The first time I came across Vim, I got pretty overwhelmed with the completely different way of text editing through the command line, so much that I didn\u2019t look back at it again. But having\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vi", "anchor_text": "vi", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://www.vim.org/", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 2}], "all_paragraphs": ["The first time I came across Vim, I got pretty overwhelmed with the completely different way of text editing through the command line, so much that I didn\u2019t look back at it again.", "But having patiently experimented with it, I am hooked. Vim has some great advanced features that I\u2019ve read about but haven\u2019t yet explored. This post is to convince you and get you started with using Vim. We\u2019ll cover the basic commands and then look into enabling syntax highlighting for Vim.", "Vim (Vi IMproved) is a clone, with additions, of Bill Joy\u2019s vi text editor program for Unix and Apple OS X. It can be downloaded for Windows here.", "Vim is a definite essential when working with bash terminals. You can edit files like your .bash_profile, for instance, with the command-line interface directly. It\u2019s a great skill to have. It being a highly customisable text editor, it can be used by anyone \u2014 software developer, data analyst, data scientist. It\u2019s a free and powerful tool that you mustn\u2019t throw out the window. Being a console editor, it works intimately with the shell. This is one of the first steps in getting comfortable navigating the shell, after which you can do pretty much everything that you need to do as a programmer.", "To open a file in Vim, type vi <name-of-the-file> in the terminal. I\u2019ll be using an empty bash script, script1.sh as an example.", "vi script1.sh : opens up the file.", "If you try to type anything, nothing will show up, as it is NORMAL mode. To edit the file, press i on the keyboard. This is the INSERT mode where the editing happens.", "Notice the INSERT in yellow at the bottom of the window.", "Once you\u2019re happy with the changes, you\u2019ll have to get out of the INSERT mode. To switch between different modes, we use the ESC key.", "To save: Press ESC and :w.", "You can also see the number of lines and characters written.", "These two commands can be clubbed as: :wq", "Remember to ESC to switch modes!", "To permanently (because, of course, we don\u2019t want it to be a one-time thing!) add syntax highlighting, we edit the .vimrc file (hidden file).", ".vimrc stands for Vim Runtime Configuration. It saves the default settings for the editor when it is opened, allowing users to customize options for the editor.", "To open the .vimrc file in Vim: vi ~/.vimrcThis file resides in your home directory and to avoid changing directories, we add a ~ (which is a shortcut for home directory).", "To edit the file: press i and add syntax on.ESC and :w to save.", "When you save, you\u2019ll see syntax highlighting in the file.:q to exit.", "To get a list of the color schemes available:", "This is in your root directory and if you\u2019re trying to find it, don\u2019t fret. /usr is a hidden folder which you can see by pressing command+shift+.", "Now to sample these color schemes and choose the one you like the most, open a file in vim.", "Keep trying out different ones till you settle on the scheme that you like the best!", "Note that the colorscheme changed through Vim is only for the current Vim session and is not saved. To permanently use a particular colorscheme, we have to add it to .vimrc :", "If you want to disable colorschemes then edit your .vimrc file by following the same steps as above and the changing the syntax on to syntax off.", "Ever since I\u2019ve gotten the hang of this, I just love working with shells and Vim. Hope you do too!", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Software Engineer @Apple | Reader | Writer | The Sustainable Edit"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2Fb4e09374df57&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvim-the-ubiquitous-text-editor-b4e09374df57&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvim-the-ubiquitous-text-editor-b4e09374df57&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fvim-the-ubiquitous-text-editor-b4e09374df57&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&